Introduction¶

1.1: Background and History¶

Online streaming platforms have taken over the media industry and has changed the way we consume movies, tv shows, and videos. With the convenience of watching media from the comfort of your home, traditional ways of watching your favorite movies and shows such as going to the theaters or buying cable are increasingly becoming unpopular. As new competitors of streaming platforms arise, it is useful to look at each platform's media inventory and see how they differtiate from each other. If all streaming platforms offered the same movies/shows, neither platform will have a competitive edge. In this EDA, we are going to look at a couple of various components: How do target age groups differentiate from each platform? Do movie genres differ between each? How can we determine the quality of movies provided? 

After exploring this data with me, I hope that the reader can gain a better understanding of the types of target demographics a platform has and how we could possibly predict what types of movies will be added to the platform in the future. As an huge fan of Netflix, it will be interesting to see how other platforms work to cater specific tastes.

Data Collection¶

2.1 Dataset Information and Source¶

I sourced this dataset from Kaggle.
Link: https://www.kaggle.com/ruchi798/movies-on-netflix-prime-video-hulu-and-disney

The dataset contains information about all movies available in either Netflix, Hulu, Prime Video, or Disney+. Each movie has information about its title, release year, target age group, IMDb rating, Rotten Tomatoes rating, availability on platforms, directors, genres, release country, language, and runtime.

First, we have to load the csv file into a dataframe so that we may examine the dataset info.

2.2 Cleaning and Tidying Data¶

From looking at the data info, we see that there are certain columns that are of object data types. Some of this columns represent numeric values, so we will want to change its type. Additionally, there are some unneeded columns that we are not interested in looking at. Also, we want to change some the text formatting in certain columns, so that we'll be able to better visualize the data later on. We are going to drop the Unnamed: 0, ID, and Type columns, reformat the IMDb, Rotten Tomatoes, and Age columns so that they only contain numeric values, and then covert the IMDb column to a float64 type.
In [726]:
#clean table by removing unwanted cols
data = data.drop('Unnamed: 0',axis = 1)
data = data.drop('ID',axis = 1)
data = data.drop('Type',axis = 1)

#trimming age, imdb, and rotten tomatoes to string representations of numbers
data['IMDb'] = data['IMDb'].str.replace("/10", "")
data['Rotten Tomatoes'] = data['Rotten Tomatoes'].str.replace("/100", "").astype('float')
data['Age'] = data['Age'].str.replace("+","")
        

#converting certain object types to numeric
data['IMDb'] = data['IMDb'].apply(pd.to_numeric, errors='coerce')
data = data.rename(columns = {"Age":"Age+"})
data.info()

Now when we examine the data, we see that there are various NaN values throughout the dataframe. We are going to want to deal with the missing data so that we can more easily visualize this data set. For the missing values in the Country, Genres, and Language column, we are going to fill them in with the modes of each. For the missing values in the IMDb and Rotten Tomatoes columns, we want fill in each value with either the average of its column if both the IMDb and Rotten Tomatoes rating is missing or with the corresponding IMDb/Rotten Tomatoes rating if only one is missing. With any missing age, we are going to use the age mode of the movie's specific streaming platform to fill it in
In [727]:
#Dealing with Missing Data

#Fill NaN 
data['Country'] = data['Country'].fillna(data['Country'].mode()[0])
data['Genres'] = data['Genres'].fillna(data['Genres'].mode()[0])
data['Language'] = data['Language'].fillna(data['Language'].mode()[0])

for i,row in data.iterrows():
    if math.isnan(data.loc[i,'IMDb']) or math.isnan(data.loc[i,'Rotten Tomatoes']):
        if math.isnan(data.loc[i,'IMDb']):
            if math.isnan(data.loc[i,'Rotten Tomatoes']) == False:
                data.loc[i,'IMDb'] = data.loc[i,'Rotten Tomatoes'] * 0.10
            else:
                data.loc[i,'IMDb'] = round(data['IMDb'].mean(),1)
                data.loc[i,'Rotten Tomatoes'] = round(data['Rotten Tomatoes'].mean(),1)
        else:
            if math.isnan(data.loc[i,'Rotten Tomatoes']):
                data.loc[i,'Rotten Tomatoes'] = data.loc[i,'IMDb'] * 10
        
    if pd.isna(data.loc[i,'Age+']):
        if data.loc[i,'Netflix'] == 1:
            data.loc[i,'Age+'] = netflix_df['Age+'].mode()[0]

Data Analysis and Visualization¶

Now, let's look at the differents genres available in each platform and examine if there are any distinctions between what types of movies each platform provides. First, we are going to create a color palette to correspond to each platform so that our graphs are more easily distinguishable. Next, we need to gather a list of all unique genres.We see that there are 27 unique movie genres across all platforms. Now we want to aggregate the movies of each genre for each platform and store them into separate dataframes containing the movie genres and total count for each genre.

#Finding all unique genres and creating bar plot of each's total
genres = []
for genre in data['Genres']:
  
    if ','in genre:
        sep_genre = genre.split(",")
    for value in sep_genre:
        if value not in genres:
            genres.append(value)
            
genres

def create_genre_table(df):
    genre_table = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Genre', 'Total'])
    genre_table['Total'] = genre_table['Total'].apply(pd.to_numeric, errors='coerce')
    genre_table['Genre'] = genres
    genre_table['Total'] = genre_table['Total'].astype('Int64')

    for i,row in genre_table.iterrows():
        genre_table.at[i,'Total'] = 0

    for i,df_row in df.iterrows():
        for i,row in genre_table.iterrows():
            if row['Genre'] in df_row['Genres']:
                genre_table.at[i,'Total'] += 1
    genre_table = genre_table.sort_values(by = ['Total'], ascending = False)
    return genre_table

#Create genre table

Bar Plots of Genres Across all Platforms¶

#bar plot of genres across all platforms

def bar_plot(table, color,title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(35,30))
    plt.title(title,fontname = 'serif',fontsize=50, weight = 'bold')
    plt.xlabel('Genre', fontname = 'serif',fontsize = 47,weight = 'bold')
    plt.ylabel('Total', fontname = 'serif',fontsize = 47,weight = 'bold')
    plt.xticks(fontname = 'serif',fontsize=30)
    plt.yticks(fontname = 'serif',fontsize=30)
    ax = sns.barplot(x='Total',y='Genre', data=table, palette=color)
  
    y_val = 0
    for i,row in table.iterrows():
            x_val = table.at[i,'Total']
            ax.text(y=y_val, x= x_val , 
                   s=str(x_val),
                  fontsize=27, fontname='serif', color='black')
            y_val += 1

    plt.show()
   
    
bar_plot(all_genre_table,all_palette,'Movie Genres Across Streaming Platforms')
bar_plot(netflix_table,netflix_palette,'Movie Genres Across Netflix')
bar_plot(hulu_table,hulu_palette,'Movie Genres Across Hulu')
bar_plot(pv_table,prime_palette,'Movie Genres Across Amazon Prime Video')
bar_plot(disney_table,disney_palette,'Movie Genres Across Disney+')

From the graphs aboves, we can see that the most popular genre across all platforms is Drama. But let's examine each platforms individual genres. For Netflix, Hulu, and Prime Video, the largest genre in quantity is Drama as well. They also have the same top 5 genres: Drama, Comedy, Thriller, Romance, and Action. However, if we look at Disney, we see that their top 5 genres are wildly different: Family, Comedy, Adventure, Animation, Fantasy. Looking at the differences in genres, it seems as though Disney+ might be catering to a different audience as opposed to the other 3. Let's take a look.
We are now going to plot the age groups across the streaming platforms using the same stratgies that we did for plotting the genre.
In [730]:
#Create dataframe of age groups across streaming platforms
ages = []
for age in data['Age+']:
    if age not in ages:
        ages.append(age)


def create_age_table(age_table,df,age_list):
    age_table['Ages'] = age_list
    age_table['Total'] = age_table['Total'].apply(pd.to_numeric, errors='coerce')
    age_table['Total'] = age_table['Total'].astype('Int64')
    for i,row in age_table.iterrows():
        age_table.at[i,'Total'] = 0
        
    for index,row in df.iterrows():
        age_row = row['Age+']
    
        if age_row == '18':
            i = 0
        elif age_row == '16':
            i = 1
        elif age_row == '13':
            i = 2
        elif age_row == '7':
            i = 3
        else:
            i = 4
        age_table.at[i,'Total'] += 1
        
    return age_table

def age_bar_plot(table, color,title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
    plt.title(title,fontname = 'serif',fontsize=22, weight = 'bold')
    plt.xlabel('Movie Age Group', fontname = 'serif',fontsize = 20,weight = 'bold')
    plt.ylabel('Total', fontname = 'serif',fontsize = 20,weight = 'bold')
    plt.xticks(fontname = 'serif',fontsize=15)
    plt.yticks(fontname = 'serif',fontsize=15)
    sns.set_context(rc = {'patch.linewidth': 1.0})
    ax = sns.barplot(x='Ages',y='Total', data=table, palette=color,errwidth=5)
    
  

    for i,row in table.iterrows():
            y_val = table.at[i,'Total']
            
            ax.text(y=y_val, x= i , 
                   s=str(y_val),
                  fontsize=13, fontname='serif', color='black')
 
    plt.show()

age_bar_plot(netflix_age,netflix_palette,'Movie Age Groups Across Netflix')
age_bar_plot(hulu_age,hulu_palette,'Movie Age Groups Across Hulu')
age_bar_plot(pv_age,prime_palette,'Movie Age Groups Across Amazon Prime Video')
age_bar_plot(disney_age,disney_palette,'Movie Age Groups Across Disney+')

Interestingly enough, we do see key differences! Netflix and Prime Video are similar in that their top 2 age demographics are "All Ages" and "18+". For Netflix, Prime Video, and Disney+, their top demographic is "All Ages" which makes sense as a streaming platform would want to maximize their audiences by making as many movies as possible appropriate for all audiences. However, something interesting to note that I personally did not expect was the difference in Hulu's age demographics. For Hulu, an extreme majority of their movies are specifically for 18+. This seems to suggest that Hulu was created for young adult content and marketed towards that audience. Netflix and Amazon Prime Video seem to be more universal in their audiences. Disney+ strongly leans towards younger audiences, with a large proportion of their movies targets towards 13+ and 7+ audiences.

Machine Learning Algorithm¶

We will use a Linear regression, decision tree, and linear svm to see how we can make better predictions. A regression model will help us reduce our mean squared error with our predictions between our x and y. In this case, our x and y is the runtime and Rotten Tomatoes rating. A decision tree helps us to follow a path of if-else statements that will lead us to information about the vairable we are going to predict. A linear svm will also allow us to test the accuracy of our predictions. From our results, we see that all measure have a fairly low accuracy. Linear SVM produces the most accurate results. This low accuracy could lead us to explore other metric that we could possibly use to determine the quality of the movie, which could aid in each platform's decision about what movies to add.
In [779]:
#Machine Learning Algorithm
data = data.rename(columns = {"Rotten Tomatoes":"rotten_tomatoes"})
data['Runtime'] = data['Runtime'].fillna(data['Runtime'].mean())

regression = linear_model.LinearRegression()
runtime = [[x] for x in data['Runtime'].values]
rating = [[y] for y in data['rotten_tomatoes'].values]
regModel = regression.fit(runtime, rating)
print("Coefficients: \n", regModel.coef_)
rating_y_pred = regModel.predict(runtime)
print("Mean squared error: %.2f" % mean_squared_error(rating, rating_y_pred))
print("Intercept: ", regModel.intercept_)
print("Coefficient of determination: %.2f" % r2_score(rating, rating_y_pred))
print("Predictions: \n", rating_y_pred)


model = ols(formula = "rotten_tomatoes ~ runtime", data = data)
fitted_model = model.fit()
print("P-Value: \n", fitted_model.f_pvalue)
print(fitted_model.params)

Conclusion¶

From our analysis, we can see that each platform has different target demographics that affect what movies they put out for their audience. With streaming platforms becoming the new mainstream form of media consumption, it is useful to analyze how streaming platform companies can determine which movies they put out in order to maximize revenue and audience retention. For further data analysis on this, it might be useful to look at the gross income each movies brings to the platform and look at the charateristics of the highest grossing movies.
